							<span id=3D"hs_cos_wrapper_post_body" class=3D"hs_cos_wrapper hs_cos=
_wrapper_meta_field hs_cos_wrapper_type_rich_text" style=3D"" data-hs-cos-g=
eneral-type=3D"meta_field" data-hs-cos-type=3D"rich_text"><p>Firewood stora=
ge and seasoning are vital to good wood burning. To <a href=3D"https://www.=
hy-c.com/blog/best-burn-practices" rel=3D"noopener"><span>get maximum effic=
iency out of your firewood</span></a>, it=E2=80=99s important to store it c=
orrectly and let the moisture evaporate from it. It=E2=80=99s typically wis=
e to aim for wood with a moisture content below 20%.</p>
<!--more-->
<p>Since firewood dimensions and weight tend to vary quite a bit from log t=
o log, it=E2=80=99s easier to talk about firewood storage in terms of one l=
arge stack of logs. These stacks are composed of units called <strong>cords=
</strong>. Firewood is typically cut, bought, and sold in these units (or f=
ractions of them).</p>
<p><span style=3D"background-color: transparent;">But what is a cord? How m=
any logs are in a cord? How much does a cord weigh? And how are cords divid=
ed to measure smaller stacks of firewood more precisely?</span></p>
<p>In this guide, we=E2=80=99re going to answer all of those questions and =
more. By the time you=E2=80=99re finished here, you=E2=80=99ll know everyth=
ing you need to know about cord sizes, dimensions, and weights so you know =
exactly how much firewood you need.</p>
<p><em>Use these links to jump to different cord sizes on this page:</em></=
p>
<ul>
<li aria-level=3D"1"><a href=3D"https://www.hy-c.com/blog/firewood-size-gui=
de-cords-and-face-cords#full-cord-of-wood" rel=3D"noopener">Full cord</a></=
li>
<li aria-level=3D"1"><a href=3D"https://www.hy-c.com/blog/firewood-size-gui=
de-cords-and-face-cords#a-1-2-cord-of-wood" rel=3D"noopener">1/2 cord</a></=
li>
<li aria-level=3D"1"><a href=3D"https://www.hy-c.com/blog/firewood-size-gui=
de-cords-and-face-cords#face-cord-of-wood" rel=3D"noopener">Face cord</a></=
li>
<li aria-level=3D"1"><a href=3D"https://www.hy-c.com/blog/firewood-size-gui=
de-cords-and-face-cords#a-1-4-cord-of-wood" rel=3D"noopener">1/4 cord</a></=
li>
<li aria-level=3D"1"><a href=3D"https://www.hy-c.com/blog/firewood-size-gui=
de-cords-and-face-cords#a-1-2-face-cord-of-wood" rel=3D"noopener">1/2 face =
cord</a></li>
</ul>
<h2 style=3D"font-size: 30px;">Cord of Wood Dimensions</h2>
<p>Let=E2=80=99s start with an overview and work our way down. There are ge=
nerally five units of cord measurements used to describe firewood storage:<=
/p>
<ul>
<li aria-level=3D"1">A full cord</li>
<li aria-level=3D"1">1/2 of a cord</li>
<li aria-level=3D"1">1/3 of a cord (also called a face cord)</li>
<li aria-level=3D"1">1/4 of a cord</li>
<li aria-level=3D"1">1/6 of a cord (also called a =C2=BD face cord)</li>
</ul>
<p>It=E2=80=99s helpful to think about cords of wood in terms of a few fami=
liar measurements:</p>
<ul>
<li aria-level=3D"1"><strong>Weight</strong> of a cord of wood</li>
<li aria-level=3D"1"><strong>Number of logs</strong> in a cord of wood</li>
<li aria-level=3D"1"><strong>Volume</strong> of a cord of wood</li>
<li aria-level=3D"1"><strong>Dimensions</strong> of a cord of wood (in term=
s of both <strong>inches</strong> and <strong>feet</strong>)</li>
</ul>
<p>The chart below lays out all of this information for the five most commo=
nly used cord wood measurements:</p>
<div data-hs-responsive-table=3D"true" style=3D"overflow-x: auto; max-width=
: 100%; width: 100%; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;">
<table>
<tbody>
<tr style=3D"height: 85px;">
<td style=3D"width: 16.6463%; height: 85px;">&nbsp;</td>
<td style=3D"width: 16.6463%; height: 85px;">
<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><strong>Cord of Wood</strong></p>
</td>
<td style=3D"width: 16.6463%; height: 85px;">
<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><strong>1/2 Cord of Wood</strong></p>
</td>
<td style=3D"width: 16.6463%; height: 85px;">
<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><strong>Face Cord of Wood</strong></p>
</td>
<td style=3D"width: 16.6463%; height: 85px;">
<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><strong>1/4 Cord of Wood</strong></p>
</td>
<td style=3D"width: 16.65%; height: 85px;">
<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><strong>1/2 Face Cord of Wood</strong></p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr style=3D"height: 85px;">
<td style=3D"width: 16.6463%; height: 85px;">
<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><strong>Weight (Pounds)</strong></p>
</td>
<td style=3D"width: 16.6463%; height: 85px;">
<p style=3D"text-align: center;">3,000 - 5,000</p>
</td>
<td style=3D"width: 16.6463%; height: 85px;">
<p style=3D"text-align: center;">1,500 - 2,500</p>
</td>
