<p>While that=E2=80=99s essentially all there is to it, let=E2=80=99s dive =
a bit deeper into each unit of measurement to help understand a little bit =
more about them.</p>
<a id=3D"full-cord-of-wood" data-hs-anchor=3D"true"></a>
<h2 style=3D"font-size: 30px;"><span style=3D"color: #da291c;">Full Cord of=
 Wood</span></h2>
<p><img src=3D"https://www.hy-c.com/hs-fs/hubfs/Imported_Blog_Media/full-co=
rd-of-wood.jpg?width=3D1400&amp;height=3D700&amp;name=3Dfull-cord-of-wood.j=
pg" width=3D"1400" height=3D"700" loading=3D"lazy" alt=3D"An illustration o=
f a full cord of firewood with red markers indicating the length, width, an=
d height of the stack." style=3D"height: auto; max-width: 100%; width: 1400=
px;"></p>
<span style=3D"color: #000000;"><br></span><br><br><br><br>
<p style=3D"font-weight: bold;"><span style=3D"color: #da291c;">Overview:</=
span></p>
<br><br><br><br>
<ul>
<li><strong>Weight:</strong> 3,000 - 5,000 pounds</li>
<li><strong>Number of logs:</strong> 600 - 800 logs</li>
<li><strong>Volume:</strong> 128 cubic feet</li>
<li><strong>Dimensions (inches):</strong> 96=E2=80=9D x 48=E2=80=9D x 48=E2=
=80=9D</li>
<li><span style=3D"font-size: 18px;"><strong style=3D"color: #000000; backg=
round-color: transparent;">Dimensions (feet):</strong><span style=3D"color:=
 #000000; background-color: transparent;"> 8=E2=80=99 x 4=E2=80=99 x 4=E2=
=80=99</span></span></li>
</ul>
<br>
<p>A cord of wood comes out to 128 cubic feet of wood. It=E2=80=99s common =
for the firewood in the cord to be stacked <strong>four feet high, eight fe=
et wide, and four feet deep</strong>. Many manufacturers fabricate their <a=
 href=3D"https://www.hy-c.com/products/firewood-racks-and-accessories"><spa=
n>firewood racks</span></a> to accommodate these dimensions.<span style=3D"=
color: #000000;"></span></p>
<p>Depending on the length of your firewood, the dimensions of your cord of=
 wood may be slightly different. What most determines a cord is its size in=
 cubic feet; a cord of wood will always come out roughly to 128 cubic feet.=
<span style=3D"color: #000000;"></span></p>
<p>The weight and number of logs in a cord vary quite considerably, too. Lo=
g weight changes due to moisture level. Moist logs with high water content =
weigh considerably more, but if you <a href=3D"https://www.hy-c.com/blog/ho=
w-to-season-firewood" rel=3D"noopener">store and season your logs correctly=
</a>, they=E2=80=99ll weigh less as more water evaporates. Also, depending =
on the length, width, and height of your logs and how you stack them, you m=
ay wind up with anywhere from 600 to 800 logs in a cord.</p>
<p style=3D"font-size: 18px;"><span style=3D"color: #000000;"><span style=
=3D"color: #000000;">Usually, a cord can have either </span><strong><span s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000;">two or three rows</span></strong><span style=3D"co=
lor: #000000;"> </span><strong><span style=3D"color: #000000;">of logs</spa=
n></strong><span style=3D"color: #000000;">. If you=E2=80=99re stacking 16=
=E2=80=9D logs, you=E2=80=99ll wind up with three rows of logs for a total =
of 48=E2=80=9D (or 4 feet) of depth. If you=E2=80=99re stacking longer 24=
=E2=80=9D logs, you=E2=80=99ll wind up with two rows of logs (again reachin=
g 4 feet of total depth).</span></span></p>
<a id=3D"a-1-2-cord-of-wood" data-hs-anchor=3D"true"></a>
<h2 style=3D"font-size: 30px;"><span style=3D"color: #da291c;">1/2 Cord of =
Wood</span></h2>
<p style=3D"font-size: 18px;"><img src=3D"https://www.hy-c.com/hs-fs/hubfs/=
Imported_Blog_Media/1-2-cord-of-wood.jpg?width=3D1400&amp;height=3D700&amp;=
name=3D1-2-cord-of-wood.jpg" width=3D"1400" height=3D"700" loading=3D"lazy"=
 alt=3D"An illustration of a 1/2 cord of firewood with red markers indicati=
ng the length, width, and height of the stack." style=3D"height: auto; max-=
width: 100%; width: 1400px;"></p>
<p style=3D"font-weight: bold;"><span style=3D"color: #da291c;">Overview:</=
span></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Weight:</strong> 1,500 - 2,500 pounds</li>
<li><strong>Number of logs:</strong> 300 - 400 logs</li>
<li><strong>Volume:</strong> 64 cubic feet</li>
<li><strong>Dimensions (inches):</strong> 96=E2=80=9D x 48=E2=80=9D x 24=E2=
=80=9D</li>
<li><span style=3D"font-size: 18px;"><strong style=3D"color: #000000; backg=
round-color: transparent;">Dimensions (feet):</strong><span style=3D"color:=
 #000000; background-color: transparent;"> 8=E2=80=99 x 4=E2=80=99 x 2=E2=
=80=99</span></span></li>
</ul>
<p>A 1/2 cord of wood is simply a cord cut in half. Again, the number to pa=
y attention to is volume, and a 1/2 cord will contain about 64 cubic feet o=
f firewood. A 1/2 cord of wood tends to measure about <strong>four feet hig=
h, eight feet long, and two feet deep</strong>.<span style=3D"color: #00000=
0;"><span style=3D"color: #000000;"></span></span></p>
<p>With a 1/2 cord, you begin to see just how important a role wood length =
plays in determining the size of your wood stack. In order to constitute a =
1/2 cord, the firewood in the stack needs to measure about 24=E2=80=9D in l=
ength (for a total of 2 feet of depth).</p>
<a id=3D"face-cord-of-wood" data-hs-anchor=3D"true"></a>
<h2 style=3D"font-size: 30px;"><span style=3D"color: #da291c;">Face Cord of=
 Wood</span></h2>
<p><img src=3D"https://www.hy-c.com/hs-fs/hubfs/Imported_Blog_Media/face-co=
rd-of-wood.jpg?width=3D1400&amp;height=3D700&amp;name=3Dface-cord-of-wood.j=
pg" width=3D"1400" height=3D"700" loading=3D"lazy" alt=3D"An illustration o=
f a face cord of firewood with red markers indicating the length, width, an=
d height of the stack." style=3D"height: auto; max-width: 100%; width: 1400=
px;"></p>
<p style=3D"font-weight: bold;"><span style=3D"color: #da291c;">Overview:</=
span></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Weight:</strong> 1,000 - 1,600 pounds</li>
<li><strong>Number of logs:</strong> 200 - 270 logs</li>
<li><strong>Volume:</strong> 42=E2=85=94 cubic feet</li>
<li><strong>Dimensions (inches):</strong> 96=E2=80=9D x 48=E2=80=9D x 16=E2=
=80=9D</li>
<li><span style=3D"font-size: 18px;"><strong style=3D"color: #000000; backg=
round-color: transparent;">Dimensions (feet):</strong><span style=3D"color:=
 #000000; background-color: transparent;"> 8=E2=80=99 x 4=E2=80=99 x 1=E2=
=85=93=E2=80=99</span></span></li>
</ul>
<p>A face cord is 1/3 of a cord. It=E2=80=99s called a face cord because th=
e height of the stack (four feet) and the length of the stack (eight feet) =
=E2=80=94 the dimensions of the =E2=80=9Cface=E2=80=9D of a full cord =E2=
=80=94 remain unchanged. The difference, again, is log length. 16=E2=80=9D =
logs stacked four feet by eight feet comprise a face cord.<span style=3D"co=
lor: #000000;"></span></p>
<p>Once again, the weight of a face cord can vary by hundreds of pounds dep=
ending on how well-seasoned (or not) the firewood is. Also, depending on th=
e width and height of your firewood, a face cord may contain anywhere from =
200 to about 270 logs.</p>
<a id=3D"a-1-4-cord-of-wood" data-hs-anchor=3D"true"></a>
<h2>1/4 Cord of Wood</h2>
<p><img src=3D"https://www.hy-c.com/hs-fs/hubfs/Imported_Blog_Media/1-4-cor=
d-of-wood.jpg?width=3D1400&amp;height=3D700&amp;name=3D1-4-cord-of-wood.jpg=
" width=3D"1400" height=3D"700" loading=3D"lazy" alt=3D"An illustration of =
a 1/4 cord of firewood with red markers indicating the length, width, and h=
eight of the stack." style=3D"height: auto; max-width: 100%; width: 1400px;=
"></p>
<p style=3D"font-weight: bold;"><span style=3D"color: #da291c;">Overview:</=
span></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Weight:</strong> 750 - 1,250 pounds</li>
<li><strong>Number of logs:</strong> 150 - 200 logs</li>
<li><strong>Volume:</strong> 32 cubic feet</li>
<li><strong>Dimensions (inches):</strong> 48=E2=80=9D x 48=E2=80=9D x 24=E2=
=80=9D</li>
<li><span style=3D"font-size: 18px;"><strong style=3D"color: #000000; backg=
round-color: transparent;">Dimensions (feet):</strong><span style=3D"color:=
 #000000; background-color: transparent;"> 4=E2=80=99 x 4=E2=80=99 x 2=E2=
=80=99</span></span></li>
</ul>
<p>1/4 of a cord is just what it sounds like =E2=80=94 a cord of wood split=
 into fourths. Instead of the typical eight-foot length of a full cord, a 1=
/4 cord tends to be about four feet wide. Like a full cord or a 1/2 cord, a=
 1/4 cord typically uses logs that are about two feet in length.<span style=
=3D"color: #000000;"></span></p>
<p>A 1/4 cord is a decent amount of wood for a moderate wood burner. If you=
 light around 20 to 25 fires in your fireplace through the burning season, =
1/4 cord should be able to get you through.</p>
<a id=3D"a-1-2-face-cord-of-wood" data-hs-anchor=3D"true"></a>
<h2><span style=3D"color: #da291c;">1/2 Face Cord of Wood</span></h2>
<p><img src=3D"https://www.hy-c.com/hs-fs/hubfs/Imported_Blog_Media/1-2-fac=
e-cord-of-wood.jpg?width=3D1400&amp;height=3D700&amp;name=3D1-2-face-cord-o=
f-wood.jpg" width=3D"1400" height=3D"700" loading=3D"lazy" alt=3D"An illust=
ration of a 1/2 face cord of firewood with red markers indicating the lengt=
h, width, and height of the stack." style=3D"height: auto; max-width: 100%;=
 width: 1400px;"></p>
<p style=3D"font-weight: bold;"><span style=3D"color: #da291c;">Overview:</=
span></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Weight:</strong> 500 - 800 pounds</li>
<li><strong>Number of logs:</strong> 100 - 140 logs</li>
<li><strong>Volume:</strong> 21-=E2=85=93 cubic feet</li>
<li><strong>Dimensions (inches):</strong> 48=E2=80=9D x 48=E2=80=9D x 16=E2=
=80=9D</li>
<li><span style=3D"font-size: 18px;"><strong style=3D"color: #000000; backg=
round-color: transparent;">Dimensions (feet):</strong><span style=3D"color:=
 #000000; background-color: transparent;"> 4=E2=80=99 x 4=E2=80=99 x 1=E2=
=85=93=E2=80=99</span></span></li>
</ul>
<p>Finally, the smallest unit on this list is the 1/2 face cord (also known=
 as 1/6 of a cord of wood). Like the 1/4 cord, a 1/2 face cord generally me=
asures about four feet tall and four feet wide. Similarly to a face cord, t=
he logs in a 1/2 face cord stack tend to be about 16 inches in length.<span=
 style=3D"font-size: 18px;"><span style=3D"color: #000000; background-color=
: transparent;"></span></span></p>
<p>Clocking in at just over 21 cubic feet, a 1/2 face cord is the perfect a=
mount of firewood for light wood burners. If you only use your fireplace a =
few times a year, 1/2 of a face cord is plenty to get you through.</p>
<h2 style=3D"font-size: 30px;">How Should You Store Your Firewood?</h2>
<p>And that=E2=80=99s everything you need to know about cords of wood. All =
the dimensions are driven from the original 128-cubic-feet full cord. From =
that unit, it=E2=80=99s just a matter of changing a width here or a length =
there to wind up with the right amount of wood to get you through the burni=
ng season.</p>
<p>But what=E2=80=99s the best way to store your stack of firewood?</p>
<p>Our guide to <a href=3D"https://www.hy-c.com/blog/best-burn-practices"><=
span>best burn practices</span></a> covers that topic in depth. From splitt=
ing, stacking, covering, and storing wood, it=E2=80=99ll help you understan=
d how to burn your firewood with maximum efficiency.</p>
<p>Also, it=E2=80=99s <strong>never a good idea to pile your wood on the gr=
ound</strong>. That exposes it to insects, critters, and the buildup of moi=
sture due to precipitation. The optimal way to store your firewood to preve=
nt these problems is <strong>by using a log rack</strong>.</p>
<p>At HY-C, we manufacture log racks that can hold over a full cord of fire=
wood =E2=80=94 and we make them right here in the USA. Find yours today by =
using our product locator!</p>
